@unpublished{Chelberg-Yang:94,
   author = {David M. Chelberg and An-doo Yang},
   note = {work reported online at http://dynamo.ecn.purdue.edu/Researchsummary/Section5/sec5\_30.html},
   title = "Improving the Results of Object Recognition and Localization
using Probabilistic Methods",
   year = {1994},
   annote = "
Overview
http://dynamo.ecn.purdue.edu/Researchsummary/Section5/sec5\_30.html 

Due to the fact that there are always some noise, errors, and
ambiguities resulting from image formation and segmentation,
measurements obtained from images are never perfect and are likely to
affect the results of  object recognition and localization. Therefore,
most object recognition systems use many parameters, such as  error
margins, for the matching process. However, there is currently no
general method to choose appropriate   values for these parameters.
The reliability and robustness of the systems are thus reduced.
Moreover, errors and ambiguities commonly exist at each step of
recognition and localization processes. Without taking these
uncertainties into account, the computed quantities may not be
accurate. We are investigating a probabilistic methodology which will
give a comprehensive basis for setting parameter values and also
account for uncertainties so better measurements can be obtained.   
"
}

